.H 1 "Accessing Registry Objects"
.P
.iX "-[" "registry" "accessing objects"
This chapter describes the permissions that apply to objects in the
registry.  Because the permissions that are granted are based on the
way the registry database is structured, this chapter first briefly
describes the structure of the registry database.  It then describes
the permissions for each object in the registry database, the registry
ACL managers, and the initial registry ACLs.
.P
Both \*Ldcecp\*O and the \*Lacl_edit\*O
command have functions for creating, modifying, and deleting ACL entries for
registry objects.  See each command's reference page in the \*(Ar for
a description of the operations it performs on ACL entries.
.H 2 "The Registry Database"
.P
.iX "-[" "registry" "database" "structure and contents"
The registry is structured into the following main directories:
.ML
.LI
The \*Lprincipal\*O directory\(emContains information about principals
.LI
The \*Lgroup\*O directory\(emContains information about groups
.LI
The \*Lorg\*O directory\(emContains information about organizations
.LE
.P
.P
In addition to the directories, the registry contains the \*Lpolicy\*O object,  
the \*Lreplist\*O object, and the \*Lxattrschema\*O object, all of which are 
created when the registry is created during machine configuration. 
The \*Lpolicy\*O object contains information that
applies to registry properties and policies and organization policies;  the
\*Lreplist\*O object contains information about the replicas in the
DCE cell; and the \*Lxattrschema\*O object contains information about 
extended registry attributes (ERAs).  
You can modify \*Lpolicy\*O and \*Lreplica\*O information at any time by using
the \*Ldcecp registry\*O commands.  The
\*Lxattrschema\*O object is modified by using the \*Ldcecp xattrschema\*O commands.
.P
When you create simple objects in the \*Lprincipal\*O, \*Lgroup\*O,
or \*Lorg\*O directory,
subdirectories are created as needed.  For example, if you add a principal
such as \*Lpreludes/villa/lobos\*O, the subdirectories \*Lpreludes\*O and
\*Lvilla\*O are created.  You can use these subdirectories to help
organize your data.  When you delete all objects in a subdirectory,
the subdirectory itself is deleted.  (You cannot delete the \*Lprincipal\*O,
\*Lgroup\*O, or \*Lorg\*O directory.)
.P  
The permissions that are granted to objects in the registry depend on where
the object fits in the structure of the registry database.  Figure 41-1 
illustrates the registry
database.  The boxes represent container objects (directories). 
The ovals represent simple objects.  Figure 41-1 shows only the top
level \*Lprincipal\*O, \*Lgroup\*O, and \*Lorg\*O directories.  Your registry
can have subdirectories if you create them. 
.P 
.FG "The Registry Database Structure"
.nL
.po -1.0i
